mother is a working mother, the bumper sticker proclaims, but the work mothers do pays no wages. Mink argues that women's equality depends on economic support for caregivers'work.Welfare's End challenges the ways in which policymakers define the problem they seek to cure. While legislators assume that something is wrong with poor single mothers, Mink insists that something is wrong with a system that invades their rights and negates their work. Showing how welfare reform harms women, Mink invites the design of policies to promote gender justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPoor womenxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic welfarezUnited States. 0aUnmarried mothersxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWelfare recipientszUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aGender Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172887740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501728877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501728877/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles